> but the old source code using the old form of the method will compile without changes

That's true for callers, but technically anyone can subclass `Workspace` and an override of `InstallPluginAsync` in a subclass won't be source compatible with the new signature. That said, I highly doubt anyone outside this assembly is subclassing `Workspace`. So I'm good with the binary break and breaking other subclasses of `Workspace`, as long as we maintain source compat for callers.

In terms of maintaining source compat, @orionstudt, is there any benefit to the extension method over keeping the old overload on the base class (no longer abstract with implementation that calls the new overload)?

```c#
public abstract class Workspace
{
    // Existing method, no longer abstract, calls new abstract overload.
    public Task InstallPluginAsync(string name, string version, PluginKind kind = PluginKind.Resource, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
        => InstallPluginAsync(name, version, kind, null, cancellationToken);

    // New abstract overload.
    public abstract Task InstallPluginAsync(string name, string version, PluginKind kind = PluginKind.Resource, PluginInstallOptions? options = null, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default);
}
```

