@TheKevJames @jonathan-johnston 
acknowledging endpoint is "all-or-nothing" in a sense that it's always "all" if you could get through network, authentication and validation:
>Acknowledging a message whose ack deadline has expired may succeed, but such a message may be redelivered later. Acknowledging a message more than once will not result in an error.

So basically if we got a response there is nothing left to do about those ids. That's why "messages failing to ack" is not even a concept here.

Google does not mention any specific limit for this endpoint. For publishing messages it is 1000 messages or 10MB, so I think it's safe to only keep 1000 messages between post attempts?

@jonathan-johnston acker backpressure is actually an interesting topic. I'd argue we don't need it _mostly_, because if a batch failed to ack, best we can do is to try again. But the priority should always go to the most recent messages, because those have higher chances to succeed in time. If we make acker a "fair" worker that wants to reliably ack everything we effectively will be increasing damage caused by random hiccups.

