I guess my point is that, if I ask someone to write a unit test for exactly what you said "This test checks that not providing any arguments will cause the help message to be displayed.", no one would ever monkeypatch the platform. That's reason enough to skip. Furthermore, if the check changes in CLI to use anything else than `sys.platform`, this test will fail and need change.

There are only 2 tests left, but before you forced push there would have been 3 places to change, maybe unlikely but still. I would at least define a fixture to keep this platform monkeypatch reusable.
I would skip it using:
```
skip_unsupported = pytest.mark.skipif(sys.platform != 'linux',
                                      reason="platform not supported")

@skip_unsupported
def test_help(monkeypatch, capsys):
```

or monkeypatch it:
```
@pytest.fixture
def _mock_platform_check(monkeypatch):
    monkeypatch.setattr(sys, "platform", "linux")


mock_platform_check = pytest.mark.usefixtures("_mock_platform_check")

@mock_platform_check
def test_help(monkeypatch, capsys):
```
that way, no need to modify everywhere in case of a change in CLI implementation.

The `skip_unsupported ` is at least not dependent on the usage of `sys.platform` in CLI but would fail to skip if the check in CLI changes to only allow x86/x86_64 architectures for example. Also, it'll still skip the tests if darwin/windows gets supported.

The `mock_platform_check` is still dependent on CLI check implementation, test will fail on other architectures if the check in CLI changes to only allow x86/x86_64 architectures for example.

A more robust way to mock or skip would be to have a function in the main module that does the platform check. It could be mocked or used for skipping in a more robust way.
```
def _platform_supported():
    if sys.platform != 'linux':
        print('Error: This tool only supports Linux')
        return False
    return True


def main():
    if not _platform_supported():
        return 1
```
